Comparison of Common DOS and Linux Commands
@ Copies files
W : copy
L : cp
Basic Linux Example : cp thisfile.txt /home/thisdirectory

@ Moves files
W : move
L : mv
Basic Linux Example : mv thisfile.txt /home/thisdirectory

@ Lists files
W : dir
L : ls
Basic Linux Example : ls

@ Clears screen
W : cls
L : clear
Basic Linux Example : clear

@ Closes shell prompt
W : exit
L : exit
Basic Linux Example : exit

@ Displays or sets date
W : date
L : date
Basic Linux Example : date

@ Deletes files
W : del
L : rm
Basic Linux Example : rm thisfile.txt

@ "Echoes" output to the screen
W : echo
L : echo
Basic Linux Example : echo this message

@ Edits text files
W : edit
L : gedit([a])
Basic Linux Example : gedit thisfile.txt

@ Compares the contents of files
W : fc
L : diff
Basic Linux Example : diff file1 file2

@ Finds a string of text in a file
W : find
L : grep
Basic Linux Example : grep word or phrase thisfile.txt

@ Formats a diskette
W : format a: (if diskette is in A:)
L : mke2fs
Basic Linux Example : /sbin/mke2fs /dev/fd0 (/dev/fd0 is the Linux equivalent of A:)

@ Displays command help
W : command /?
L : man or info
Basic Linux Example : man command

@ Creates a directory
W : mkdir
L : mkdir
Basic Linux Example : mkdir directory

@ Views contents of a file
W : more
L : less([b])
Basic Linux Example : less thisfile.txt

@ Renames a file
W : ren
L : mv([c])
Basic Linux Example : mv thisfile.txt thatfile.txt

@ Displays your location in the file system
W : chdir
L : pwd
Basic Linux Example : pwd

@ Changes directories with a specified path (absolute path)
W : cd pathname
L : cd pathname
Basic Linux Example : cd /directory/directory

@ Changes directories with a relative path
W : cd..
L : cd ..
Basic Linux Example : cd ..

@ Displays the time
W : time
L : date
Basic Linux Example : date

@ Shows amount of RAM in use
W : mem
L : free
Basic Linux Example : free

@ 
W : 
L : 
Basic Linux Example : 

@ 
W : 
L : 
Basic Linux Example : 
